3/ped.xml:[customarily expl&lt;sup&gt;d&lt;/sup&gt; as ava+&lt;b&gt;lañj&lt;/b&gt; (cp. Geiger &lt;i&gt;P.Gr.&lt;/i&gt; § 66&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;), the root &lt;b&gt;lañj&lt;/b&gt; being given as a Sk. root in meaning "to fry," "to be strong," and a variety of &lt;p&gt;&lt;center&gt; -- 603 -- &lt;/center&gt;&lt;p&gt; others (see Mon. Williams s. v. &lt;b&gt;lañj&lt;/b&gt;). But the root &amp; its derivations are only found in lexicographical and grammatical works, therefore it is doubtful whether it is genuine. ;&lt;b&gt;lañja&lt;/b&gt; is given as "pada," i. e. track, place foot, and also "tail." We are inclined to see in &lt;b&gt;lañj&lt;/b&gt; a by -- form of &lt;b&gt;lañch&lt;/b&gt;, which is a variant of &lt;b&gt;lakṣ&lt;/b&gt; "to mark etc. (cp. lañcha, lañchaka, ˚ana, ˚ita). Thus the meaning would range from originally "trace," mark off enclose, to: "being enclosed," assigned or belonging to i. e. moving (in), frequenting etc., as given in C. expl&lt;sup&gt;ns&lt;/sup&gt; There seems to be a Singhalese word at the root of it as it is certainly dialectical. -- The Dhtm (522) laconically defines &lt;b&gt;valañj&lt;/b&gt; as "valañjane"]
